				<div style="margin-top:20px;">The reviews from Chrome Store generally desire for more entertaining features. The current version of Pixel Monster doesn't supply much control over the munching action, which frustrates some of the users. Most of the time people pick up the idea of subverting the web very quickly, and feel exhilarated to see images destroyed. I learned to take people's feedbacks of whether good or bad as valuable inputs to my project. While knowing about people's need, they also help clarify my own interests on the subject, and think deep about what's really interesting to me and others. I learned to balance between people's need and my own pursue, through understanding real users.</div>
			
				<div style="margin-top:20px;">The image archive and analysis of their sources on Monster website provide insights to learn about how people perceive different online images. The fact that Facebook ranks as Top 1 image source is an evidence of strong emotions many people have towards their friends in the digital Social Network, whether they are positive or negative. Some people responded that it's tiring of looking at friends' self-indulgent images, while some felt funny just to subvert familiar faces. Archived images also demonstrate peoples' intense feeling towards many subjects: Egyptian revolution, Justin Bieber, Google logos, advertising, porn, and etc.</div>
			
